<div id="outline-container-org674c517" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="org674c517">Key Terms</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-org674c517">
</div>
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="orgcb2fd74"></a>Management: the proccess of accomplishing the goals of an organization through the effective use of people and other resources<br /></li>
<li><a id="org9e2e4d2"></a>Planning: involves analyzing information and making decisions about what needs to be done<br /></li>
<li><a id="org47c6c6a"></a>Organizing: is concerned with determining how plans can be accomplished most effectively and arranging resources to complete work<br /></li>
<li><a id="org1b15d98"></a>Staffing: focuses on finidng indiviudlas with the right skills to do the work<br /></li>
<li><a id="org2d0701f"></a>Leading: requires working with employees to ensure they are motivated and have the resources needed to help carry out plans and get the work done<br /></li>
<li><a id="org6f8189a"></a>Controlling: involves evaluating results to determine if the company's objectives have been accomplished as planned<br /></li>
<li><a id="org5b81b4c"></a>Manager: completes all five management functions on a regular basis and has authority over jobs and people<br /></li>
<li><a id="org89605f7"></a>Supervisor: a manager whose main job is to direct the work of employees. They are the first level of management in a company<br /></li>
<li><a id="org2eda17c"></a>Executive: a top-level manager who spends almost all of his or her time on managmenet functions and decisions that affect the entire company<br /></li>
<li><a id="org1a33e1b"></a>Middle-Manager: completes all of the management functions, but spends most of the time completing specialized work in one management function or is responsible for a specefic part of the companys operations<br /></li>
<li><a id="org23297e7"></a>Industrial Revolution: the era of the 18th and 19th century in which machine power replaced human and animal power in the production process, leading to major business and social changes<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgc68e490"></a>Management Science: the careful, objective study of management decisions and procedures in order to improve the operation of busineses and organizations<br /></li>
<li><a id="orge5b375f"></a>Classical Management: studies the way work is organized and the procedures used to complete a job in order to increase worker productivity. Fredrick Taylor<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgb86f012"></a>Administrative Management: identifies the most effective practices for organizing and managing a business. Henri Fayol<br /></li>
<li><a id="org6404308"></a>Behavioral Management: directed at organizational improvement through understanding employee motivation and behavior. Also called Human relations management. Douglas Mcgregor and Elton Mayo<br /></li>
<li><a id="orge0d1691"></a>Quality Management: a total commitment by everyone in a organiztion to improve the quality of procedures and products by reducing waste, errors, and defects. Japan hired american engineer W. Edward Deming<br /></li>
<li><a id="org13ac80b"></a>Business Competition: the rivarly among companies for consumers<br /></li>
<li><a id="org721dfec"></a>Management Strategy: a carefully developed overall approach to leading an organization<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="org7fc8979"></a>The business<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgc838f9c"></a>The work<br /></li>
<li><a id="org563dcdf"></a>The management<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgd4877f6"></a>The Business Enviorment<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="orgbe4bfc7"></a>Workforce: becoming more diverse between 2010 and 2050<br /></li>
<li><a id="org1d0e22c"></a>Administrative management characteristics:<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="orgdd33cd0"></a>Authority and responsibility: managers have the authority to assign tasks and delegate responsibilities<br /></li>
<li><a id="org41d614e"></a>Unity of command: each employee must recieve direction from only one manager to avoid conflicts and help keep a chain of command<br /></li>
<li><a id="org8b2c3f8"></a>Unity of purpose: the goals and direction of an organization must be clear and supported by everyone<br /></li>
<li><a id="org77e72a2"></a>Adequte compensation: the wages and benefits for every employee should be fair and satisfactory to both the individual and their organization<br /></li>
<li><a id="org062a920"></a>Espirit de corps: organizations should work to build good interpersonal relationships, a sense of teamwork and harmony<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
